Response 3:
Since the most feasible clinical symptomatic differential diagnosis is common cold; the following drug regimen should be prescribed:-
- Paracetamol  (tap, 500 mg)
Sig. 1 tab P.O. prn for fever q 6 h
As to relieve feverish discomfort and associated troubling symptoms such as headache or myalgia. (including malaise, ear pain or sneezing if present)
-Chlorpheniramine (tab, 4 mg); it is an oral histamine-1 receptor antagonist.
Sig. 1 tab P.O. tid pc +hs
As to relieve rhinorrhea and allergic symptoms. Nevertheless, anticholinergic reactions such as dry mouth and eyes, sedation with/without confusion and miscellaneous side effects, e.g. weight gain and prolonged QT interval or cardiac arrhythmias should likewise be informed regarding to patient autonomy. 
However, with nasal congestion and tussive characteristics of this patient, decongestant and antitussive drug should be at least considered if compliant by the patient.
Pseudoephedrine or phenylephrine combined with antihistamine medication for relieving nasal congestion. BUT nasal congestive symptoms is not intolerable, so these drugs should be prescribed otherwise appropriated. Nasal tropical decongestant can be prescribed based on judgement of the patient worsening nasal congestion despite oral drugs given or to avoid sedative effects of such drugs:-
Ephedrine or Oxymetazoline can be given. (the patient must be informed that prolonged use of the latter drug can induce rebound congestion of nasopharyngeal mucosa.
    Clinician should be noted that giving antimicrobial drugs is not recommended for common cold because it is self-limited (usually lasts up to 10 days) and finding the sources of superimposed infection is required incase of the predominant symptoms is of the infection itself or upper airway infection complication is present in case of chronic symptoms or suspected host etiologic origin such as allergic rhinitis or deviant nasal septum. Resting and adequate fluid intake is recommended to avoid exacerbation of cold symptoms (e.g. sinusitis, LRT I, asthma or acute otitis media.) Saline nasal spray or wash may help with the nasal symptoms; Vitamin C or herbal products given after remission show no reduction in symptom duration or severity.
Prevention: hand hygiene.

คนไข้รายนี้น่าจะเป็นแค่ Common cold ธรรมดา ส่วนใหญ่จะ Self-limited หายเองได้อยู่แล้ว จึงไม่ควรให้ Antibiotics และให้รักษาตามอาการพอ โดยอาการสำคัญของคนไข้รายนี้จะมี ปวดหัว, น้ำมูกไหล, คัดจมูก และไอแห้ง ๆ ไม่มีเสมหะ จึงควรให้ยาดังต่อไปนี้

4. Antitussive = Dextromethorphan tab (15 mg) ทานครั้งละ 1 เม็ด 3 เวลาหลังอาหาร (ยานี้อยู่ในบัญชียาหลักแห่งชาติ ก)
